      <h1>Gross Pay vs. Net Pay: Understanding Paycheck Deductions</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 15, 2026</span><span>·</span><span>5 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">When you get a job offer, the salary quoted is your gross pay. What actually hits your bank account is your net pay. Here is a guide to understanding the deductions in between.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>The quick definitions:</strong> <strong>Gross pay</strong> is the total amount of money you earn before any deductions are made. <strong>Net pay</strong> (also known as take-home pay) is the money you actually receive after all taxes and deductions are subtracted.</div>

      <h2>What is gross pay?</h2>
      <p>Gross pay is the starting point of your earnings calculation. For salaried employees, it is your annual salary divided by the number of pay periods in a year. For hourly employees, it is your hourly wage multiplied by the number of hours worked during the pay period, plus any overtime pay (1.5x regular rate) earned.</p>
      <p>Gross pay also includes any holiday pay, commissions, bonuses, or tips you received during the pay period.</p>

      <h2>What is net pay?</h2>
      <p>Net pay is the money that is direct-deposited into your bank account or written on your paycheck. It is the actual cash you have available to cover rent, groceries, savings, and personal spending. To get from gross pay to net pay, your employer must apply various paycheck deductions.</p>

      <h2>Common paycheck deductions explained</h2>
      <p>Deductions are split into two categories: mandatory (required by law) and voluntary (selected by you).</p>

      <h3>1. Mandatory Deductions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Federal Income Tax:</strong> Calculated based on your tax bracket and the options you selected on your W-4 form.</li>
        <li><strong>FICA Taxes:</strong> A flat 7.65% deduction consisting of 6.2% for Social Security and 1.45% for Medicare.</li>
        <li><strong>State and Local Income Tax:</strong> Levied by your state or city. Rates vary from 0% (e.g. Texas, Florida) to over 10% (e.g. California, New York).</li>
        <li><strong>State Disability/Unemployment:</strong> Some states deduct small amounts for state-run disability or family leave programs.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>2. Voluntary Deductions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Health Insurance Premiums:</strong> Medical, dental, and vision insurance costs. These are typically deducted pre-tax, lowering your overall tax bill.</li>
        <li><strong>Retirement Contributions:</strong> Contributions to traditional 401(k) or 403(b) accounts (pre-tax) or Roth accounts (post-tax).</li>
        <li><strong>HSA or FSA Contributions:</strong> Tax-free deductions to cover medical or dependent care expenses.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>A hypothetical paycheck calculation</h2>
      <p>Imagine you earn a gross pay of $2,000 per biweekly pay period. Here is how it translates to net take-home pay:</p>
      <pre><code>Gross Pay:                   $2,000.00
- Pre-tax 401(k) (5%):       -  $100.00
- Pre-tax Health Insurance:  -   $50.00
Taxable Gross Income:        $1,850.00
- Federal Income Tax (est):  -  $185.00
- FICA Taxes (7.65%):        -  $153.00
- State Income Tax (est):    -   $74.00
Net Take-Home Pay:           $1,438.00</code></pre>
